OBJECTIVE
•	To generate a continuous Triangular Wave (sawtooth/ramp pattern up and down) at Port 2 (P2) of an 8051 microcontroller by linearly incrementing and then decrementing the digital value sent to the port.

ALGORITHM
1.	Initialize: Clear the Accumulator (A = 00H).
2.	Ramp Up (Rising Edge):
	o	Output the value of A to Port 2.
	o	Increment A.
	o	Compare A with FFH. If not equal, repeat the output and increment process.
3.	Ramp Down (Falling Edge):
	o	Output the value of A to Port 2.
	o	Decrement A.
	o	Compare A with 00H. If not equal, repeat the output and decrement process.
4.	Repeat: Jump back to the start of the Ramp Up sequence to create a periodic wave.

CODE 

L1: MOV A, #00H  ; Initialize Accumulator to 0

U:  MOV P2, A    ; [Ramp Up] Move current value to Port 2
    INC A        ; Increase value by 1
    CJNE A, #0FFH, U ; Keep increasing until A reaches 255 (FFH)

D:  MOV P2, A    ; [Ramp Down] Move current value to Port 2
    DEC A        ; Decrease value by 1
    CJNE A, #00H, D  ; Keep decreasing until A reaches 0

    SJMP L1      ; Repeat the whole process infinitely

PROCEDURE

1. Power ON the 8051 Trainer Kit.
2. Enter the program by selecting the A (Address) option and specifying the starting address 4100.
3. Enter the code instructions sequentially. (Note: No external data input is required for this program).
4. Execute the program using the GO command followed by the starting address 4100.
5. Verify the output by connecting a Digital-to-Analog Converter (DAC) to Port 2, then connect the DAC output to an Oscilloscope to observe the triangular waveform.

EXPECTED OUTPUT

8051 outputs digital values, once passed through a DAC (interface circuit), the output on the oscilloscope will be a linear triangular wave.
•	Peak Voltage: Approximately +5V (at FFH).
•	Minimum Voltage: 0V (at 00H).

